the module called PeanutAckermannBenchmark
    with concern: deep recursion performance verification

the behavior called ackermann
    with intent: compute how the elephant's peanut appetite grows with spiral intensity
    takes:
        an integer called elephant-depth
        an integer called peanut-intensity
    delivers: an integer
    with diminishing: elephant-depth, peanut-intensity
    as:
        if elephant-depth matches 0
            then peanut-intensity added-to 1
            else if peanut-intensity matches 0
                then (elephant-depth decreased-by 1) utilizes ackermann 1
                else
                    -- Notice: we now use n-dimensional diminishing variables to cache this growth spiral
                    derivation: spiral-step derives-from elephant-depth utilizes ackermann (peanut-intensity decreased-by 1)
                    (elephant-depth decreased-by 1) utilizes ackermann spiral-step

the effect behavior called run
    with intent: demonstrate the 100x speedup from multi-dimensional memoization
    takes: nothing
    delivers: an integer
    as:
        -- Ackermann(3, 11) normally triggers millions of recursive steps
        derivation: depth_value     derives-from 3
        derivation: intensity_value derives-from 11
        derivation: result derives-from depth_value utilizes ackermann intensity_value
        
        derivation: label   derives-from a string "Ackermann(3, 11) for the great peanut leader is: "
        derivation: msg     derives-from label joined-with (result utilizes as-text)
        broadcasts msg
        0
